    "creation_date" : 1265956205,
    "answer_id" : 2250053,
    "question_id" : 2250031,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>You could potentially write a helper method which returned an empty sequence if you passed in null:</p>\n\n<pre><code>public static &lt;T&gt; Iterable&lt;T&gt; emptyIfNull(Iterable&lt;T&gt; iterable) {\n    return iterable == null ? Collections.&lt;T&gt;emptyList() : iterable;\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Then use:</p>\n\n<pre><code>for (Object object : emptyIfNull(someList)) {\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>I don't think I'd actually do that though - I'd usually use your second form. In particular, the \"or throw ex\" is important - if it really shouldn't be null, you should definitely throw an exception. You know that <em>something</em> has gone wrong, but you don't know the extent of the damage. Abort early.</p>\n"
  }, {
